ies. It explores why they are busy and what the consequences are for their lives. Busyness is not just a matter of personal time management, but of the activities we participate in and how each of us creates "the good life." While numerous books deal with efficiency and the difficulties of balancing work and family, Busier Than Ever! offers a fresh approach. Busyness is not a "problem" to be solved—it is who we are as Americans and it's redefining American families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aFamiliesxTime managementxUnited States. 0aFamiliesxTime managementzUnited States. 0aFamiliesxUnited States. 0aFamilieszUnited States. 0aParentingxUnited StatesxVerenigde StatenxUnited States. 0aParentingzUnited States. 4aAnthropology -- Cultural and Social Anthropology. 4aSociology -- Culture. 4aSociology -- Family and Youth. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aEnglish-Lueck, J.A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFreeeman, James M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476818440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768184423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768184/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles